### Finding M-001: Monthly Vulnerability Scan — High Finding in Tomcat

**Source:** AWS Inspector monthly scan, Week 6 post-authorization

**Finding:** Inspector flagged CVE-[number] in Apache Tomcat [version] — a deserialization vulnerability rated CVSS 7.8 (High) affecting the version of Tomcat bundled with the OpenMRS deployment. The vulnerability allows remote code execution if an attacker can reach the Tomcat admin interface.

**Immediate Response (Day of finding):**

Step 1 — Exploitability assessment: The ISSO reviewed the CVE details. The vulnerability requires access to the Tomcat manager application. OpenMRS's production deployment has the Tomcat manager application disabled — it was disabled during the initial hardening in Day 54 as part of CM-7 least functionality. The attack surface is significantly reduced.

Step 2 — Confirm Tomcat manager status: IT Administrator confirmed that the Tomcat manager application is disabled in the production configuration. AWS WAF rules block any requests to /manager/ paths. GuardDuty has not detected any attempts to reach the manager application in the past 30 days. CloudTrail shows no unauthorized access to the EC2 instance.

Step 3 — Determine patch timeline: Tomcat update from [current version] to [patched version] requires testing in the test environment to confirm OpenMRS compatibility — Tomcat upgrades occasionally introduce compatibility issues with OpenMRS modules. IT Administrator scheduled test environment update for the following week, production update for the week after. Total remediation window: 14 days.

**Disposition:** POA&M entry created — M-001. Severity: High (CVSS 7.8). Compensating control: Tomcat manager disabled; WAF blocking manager paths; no exploitation evidence. 14-day remediation timeline. Owner: IT Administrator. No AO notification required per classification table (High vulnerability with compensating controls and patch within SLA does not require AO notification unless the 30-day High patch SLA will be missed).

**Resolution (Day 14):** IT Administrator updated Tomcat in test environment — OpenMRS compatibility confirmed. Production update applied during scheduled maintenance window. Inspector re-scan confirmed patched version. POA&M item M-001 closed. Monitoring log entry: [date] — CVE remediated, Inspector confirmed COMPLIANT, POA&M item closed.

**SSP update required?** No — the Tomcat version change is a routine patch, not a control implementation change. Change log entry sufficient.

