## A Real-World Example That Made This Click

Finding M-004 — the internal role change creating a six-week window of over-privileged access that the prior access review template would have missed — directly connects to the pattern that OCR has repeatedly found in HIPAA enforcement actions: organizations with access control policies that address hiring and termination but fail to address the access implications of internal role changes.

The **2018 Fresenius Medical Care settlement with OCR ($3.5 million)** involved multiple breach incidents. One of the contributing factors OCR identified was insufficient workforce access management — specifically, that access controls were not consistently updated when workforce members changed roles. The investigation found that some access privileges persisted after role changes in ways that exceeded the minimum necessary standard.

The M-004 finding at MyClinic is a small-scale version of the same gap — access level not updated when job function changed. The difference is that MyClinic caught it in six weeks through a quarterly access review, before any exploitation occurred. Fresenius's failures were not caught through internal monitoring — they were surfaced through breach investigations.

This is exactly the compounding value of effective continuous monitoring: it catches the gaps that otherwise only surface when something goes wrong. Finding M-004 is a positive outcome — the monitoring worked. The process improvement (ISSO notification for internal role changes) makes the monitoring even more effective going forward.

